result.execSummary:
The defendant Tyrone F. Brown was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Child Abuse-Intentionally Cause Harm, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.03(2)(b).
  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

15CM112 - Battery

 Asks that the balance of the bond that was posted be returned to the poster.  Believes there is jail credit of 170 days on 18CF192 only. 
Atty Mukoski agrees to the jail credit as stated by Atty Schmidt. 

BY THE COURT:
15CF362 Counts 1 & 2 - 
5 years prison with 2 years Initial Confinement followed by 3 years Extended Supervision on each count - STAYED -
Count 2 is concurrent with Count 1. 
Not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration or Substance Abuse Programs.

Comply with other assessments and counseling as recommended by the agent.

15CM112 - 
30 days jail - STAYED - 
Placed on probation for a period of 1 year:
Pay costs and surcharges.

Submit a DNA sample. 

18CF192 Count 2 - 
5 years prison with 2 years Initial Confinement followed by 3 years Extended Supervision - STAYED -
171 days credit.
Not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration or Substance Abuse Programs. 
Placed on probation for a period of 3 years: 
Comply with all conditions ordered in 15CF131 and 15CF362.
Pay costs and surcharges. 
Submit a DNA sample. 

Atty Schmidt indicates credit should be 171 days since he had counted 30 days in July rather than 31. 
BY THE COURT:  So ordered.
